    <title type="text">ΑΟΙΔΟΙ: Greek poetry from the Epics to Anacreontics</title>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<span style="font-size: xx-small;">[First posted in AWOL 21 March
      2011. Updated 8 September 2013] </span><br /><br /><a
      href="http://www.aoidoi.org/">ΑΟΙΔΟΙ</a><br /><blockquote><span
      style="font-size: x-small;">"Aoidoi" is classical Greek for "bards," like Homer, or just
      "poets." This site is dedicated to the study of ancient Greek poetry from the Epics to
      Anacreontics. Most of the work is directed at producing versions of Greek poems with
      vocabulary, grammar and dialect notes for beginners.&nbsp;</span>
      </blockquote><blockquote><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><b>Dialects</b></span><br /><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><ul><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"> For the
      confused beginner, <a href="http://www.aoidoi.org/articles/dialects.html">Greek Dialects
      - Where to Start</a></span> </li><li> <span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><a href="http://www.aoidoi.org/articles/lesbian.html">Lesbian
      Aeolic</a>. </span></li><li> <span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><a href="http://www.aoidoi.org/articles/choral_doric.html">Choral
      Doric</a></span> </li><li> <span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><a href="http://www.aoidoi.org/articles/bucolic_doric.html">Bucolic
      Doric</a></span> </li></ul><span style="font-size: x-small;">
      </span><span style="font-size: x-small;"><b>Meter and
      Recitation</b></span><br /><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><ul><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"> A <a
      href="http://www.aoidoi.org/articles/meter/intro.pdf">general introduction</a> to
      Greek meter (PDF) </span></li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"> In
      <a href="http://www.aoidoi.org/articles/meter/epic_caesura.pdf">Some Comments on the Epic
      Caesura</a> I give a possible origin for the heroic hexameter, and then analyze the first
      21 lines of Iliad A with special attention to the
      caesura.</span></li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"> In <a
      href="http://www.aoidoi.org/articles/epic/recite.pdf">Reciting the Heroic
      Hexameter</a> I present one way to recite hexameters. The PDF has links to MP3 examples.
      </span></li><li> <span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.aoidoi.org/articles/caraerror.html">The Error of Caragounis</a>, a
      summary of some problems with C. Caragounis' notion that Ancient and Modern Greek are
      pronounced identically. </span></li><li><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"> A reference: <a
      href="http://www.aoidoi.org/articles/epic/digamma.html">Words with Digamma in
      Epic.</a></span> </li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;">
      Which word shapes go where: <a
      href="http://www.aoidoi.org/articles/meter/localizatio.pdf">Localization in the
      Hexameter</a>. On pp.53-57 of Chad Bochan's <a
      href="http://www.freewebs.com/mhninaeide/GrkIambicComp-23-Apr-06.pdf">notes on iambic
      comp</a> are localization tables for iambic trimeters.
      </span></li></ul><span style="font-size: x-small;">
      </span><span style="font-size: x-small;"><b>Et
      cetera</b></span><br /><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><ul><li> <span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.aoidoi.org/articles/vc/">Greek Verse Composition</a></span>
      </li><li> <span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.aoidoi.org/articles/ktl/">καὶ τὰ λοιπά</a>, my place for random
      musings on Greek or Poetic matters.</span></li></ul><span
